@davidsoulsby1102 
The cost I refer to is the long term environmental cost, which will inevitably lead to greater overall monetary costs in the long term.  Your point is well taken, when referring to industrial production costs at scale (not food production).  That is a short term model however which fails to take into account the actual cost to the environment.  We are actually getting better at remediating our destructive practices, but the extraction processes are destructive of both environment and people involved, while the end products are disposed of in further environmentally damaging ways.
  The cost of this is something that needs to be considered in your calculations.

